segments.text: president walton very good uh i'm trying to recall i don't remember the president being very close to the student body at that time we were there was a buffer i guess you could say the military of course i didn't mention them previously but they played a big role in uh
the core life and sort of administered the core at that time.
So you didn't see President Walton, your students didn't much?
No, no.
I remember one incident that...

I can't recall the exact details, but I was at a meeting one evening with a group of students of some type, I don't know, agricultural students maybe, that met with him, and he talked to us, and I was really impressed.
He was an excellent speaker, I thought, and seemed to have good understanding of the institution, and my impression at that age was very good, and
I remember Earl Rutter saying when he was a student here, they referred to the president as the Prexy.
Was that still common when you got here?
I believe that's right.
And there was a light up on top of the academic building, a light globe that they called Prexy's Moon, and he said that you would try to shoot it out with your core rifle.
I recall that now that you mention it.
I don't remember...
anyone in our area trying to do the shooting that I recall, but that was part of it.
Just had another thought, but it's already slipped my mind.
Well, you know, Dr. Walton was removed from the presidency shortly after I was here as a student.
I think it was during the war, perhaps, early 40s.
I'm
I'm sure you know the time on it.
I heard this story at the time after he had been removed.
You know he became postmaster at College Station.
You may have heard this.
He lived on the south side of the campus and he'd always drive around the campus.
He never would go through the campus anymore after he'd been let out as president and was now postmaster.
Those two undergraduate years, what did you and your friends do for a good time at Texas A&M on, say, a Saturday night?
Leave town, if possible.
And how did you get to Houston when you left town?
Catch rides.
The highway would be full starting Friday after 1 o'clock.
You
heard the old story, saw I'm sure about, had a court trip to hell, we'd want to leave early.
And normally how long did it take you hitchhiking to Houston?
That depends.
If you were fortunate, two and a half hours.
It could take five or six.
And going, coming back sometimes is even worse because there's always a question, where do you
go in Houston to catch a ride back.
Where was the best place to catch a ride in Houston?
Well, we usually got out on Hampstead Highway there off 19th Street used to run out.
Hempstead Highway, and of course, I was still going home at the time, and my parents lived in the Heights, which was fairly near to that particular location.
And if you caught a ride there, you're bound to get almost to get to Hempstead at least.
And you would certainly, coming back, you would certainly wear your uniform.
Oh, yes.
That was a key item to getting around?
Absolutely.
Well, you'd have it on actually then.
And we'd go to Dallas-Fort Worth.
Also, you talk about entertainment and so forth, it's fairly common to go to Denton to what was then TSCW, I believe it was called.
And I've been up there a fair number of weekends along with a lot of other Aggies.
Do you have any hitchhiking anecdotes
None come to mind just immediately.
No.
Did you ever have any bad experience hitchhiking?
No.
I never.
I never interviewed a single person who did.
Well, the uniform was great, and I don't remember a specific anecdote, but the people would pick you up.
You were just friends right away and have a conversation with them.
They were.
happy to pick you up and take you wherever you were.
If you were not going to leave town, what did you and your friends do for a good time?
Well, there were dances in the spring that we would go to intermittently, and there's a place called Hardlickers out here, I guess you've heard of it, that was south of the campus.
It was a refuge if you didn't have anything else to do.
Now, Mr. Hardlaker served what kind of beverages?
I believe beer was the only alcoholic beverage allowed at that time.
Of course, he had all the soft drinks, and I believe they even served a little food out there.
Was there a careful check on the age of anyone buying a beer at Mr. Hardlaker's?
I can never remember any.
And do you remember Aggies getting drunk much?
Well, I can certainly remember it, yes.
There wasn't much restraint on drinking.
It didn't seem to me.
But whiskey was a rare commodity, wasn't it?
Because this was a dry county for whiskey.
Yes, but I...
I wouldn't call it rare.
Oh, really?
It depended on the situation.
Like if there were special weekends or events, there'd be some around.
Would they have brought that from home?
To some extent, although there were two or three liquor stores right across the river that made a fortune, I suppose.
Did you all call it Whiskey Bridge then?
I believe so.
I was trying to think just what the reference was to that location, but I believe there's a store right across the Brazzers where 60 is and also out on 21.
The young ladies came for these dances.
How were those young women treated at an Aggie dance?
With respect, I would say, yes.

And I've had girls up for the dances, and not as many as some of the students would have one every weekend they'd have a dance if they were going steady with some girl from Austin or TSCW or Houston or Dallas.
And the girls usually stayed in local homes around.
In fact, well, this is getting ahead, but
Later on, we had a home south of college where we kept girls nearly every weekend in the spring.
Many of the faculty lived on campus in that era.
That is correct.
So there was a true community there on the campus of family and students and so forth.
like I've heard the two Cashin boys describe their experiences growing up on the campus.
Where was there near the campus that you could walk to buy something?
Northgate.
What was that described Northgate in that era?
Two drugstores is the main thing I remember.
One was Lipscomb's Drugstore, and it would have been on...

northwest corner and uh i believe they call the other one the aggie land pharmacy on the right corner and then there was hollick's boot store and uh cleaners down the the college avenue part there and i believe walter had a store there at the north gate
And a jeweler, I think, and just three or four.
Was the campus theater open in those days?
I don't believe so by 38.
Oh, yes, that's something I should have known.
We went in the assembly hall, and it was a wooden building.
I think they said it was built during World War I, right after World War I in that period.

uh... fire hazard if there ever was one just totally would and i think smoking was prohibited in it uh... but it was a real danger and i guess it wasn't torn down until the current chapel was built which i guess was soon after world war two but at entertainment we went to shows a lot they were just i think they just had them saturdays and maybe sundays and
Maybe Wednesday night, I've forgotten.
But you'd usually go to one or two shows a week.
Do you have some memories you can share of some Aggie good bull?
Some pranks, some jokes?
Well, I'm hard-pressed right at the moment.
That airing out thing was an experience.
I thought that justified telling.
Oh, yes, thank you.
I couldn't think of that term while ago.

Yes, in the spring particularly as it began to warm up a little, there was a lot of drowning out and I don't recall just what different occasions were used as somewhat of an excuse or a reason to do this, but that was kind of a challenge and as I recall, it usually started drowning out the fish and then
then they'd be instructed to go drown out Mr. So-and-so or this one or another.
And that was one way some of the cadets got even with some of the others they didn't think so much of.
But that went on quite a lot in the spring months.
And to get started, there was just no end to it.
The whole battery would be drowned out.
Did anybody ever attempt any pranks on a faculty member or a staff member?
I can't honestly recall any in class or out.
I don't know if this is an anecdote or not, but one of the faculty members I do recall being somewhat eccentric was Dr. Humbert.
Eugene Humbert in the genetics department, and he had several requirements of his students, and actually he didn't.
He was not the best teacher in a strict sense, but he was strict and did insist you read your lesson, but he required you to bring your book to class, and you had to wear
Socks rolled up so that your socks reached your trousers.
I've forgotten.
He had one or two other little quirks that he insisted on, and I recall one incident during the semester when something upset him a little.
Anyway, he got a little mad about something, and he said, All right.
How many people brought their books to class today?
There were about three kids.
All right, the rest of you can go home.
And he just emptied the old classroom right there.
But he would do that, that sort of thing.
As far as you recall, what was the typical attitude of the A&M student body then about going to class?
Did you all go to class regularly?
Freshmen did.
They had to be punished if they didn't, if somebody found it out.
My recollection is the higher up you went in school, the less concerned you were about going to class.
I can always remember the architect students.
We had several of them in our battery, and our captain was an architect.
student I bet I was in school two months before I ever saw him they'd go up there after dinner at night
about seven or eight o'clock and stayed till two or three or I don't know.
They were up there all night.
And man, they wouldn't get up till noon.
That's true.
I didn't even know.
They kept saying, well, Captain, I think his name was J.W.
Floor, was the battery commander.
I never had seen the fella.
And when I finally saw him, I didn't know who he was.
But that was one unusual element of the class situation or attendance situation.
I'd say the juniors and seniors, I'd say, were less committed to going to class consistently, but freshmen sure attended.
Coming from a minister's family, you should be able to describe the religious activities at A&M at that period.
I almost started to say slamming none, but it's been unfair.
No, that's really not correct.
There was not a lot of organized religious activity day to day and week to week.
There were the local churches available, and I did go along with some of the other students to the Presbyterian Church, and we would have a meeting Sunday nights that Reverend Anderson conducted.
Describe that congregation during those years, and who were some of the notable members?
You're talking about the church congregation.

It was small, I'd say, ordinary attendance, and we met in, the Presbyterian congregation met in the Y, YMCA, and I guess there were probably 100 to 150 probably in attendance, and that's about all the chapel there would hold, and mostly local people.
There'd be
I guess the student attendance varied from I'm going to say 20 to 40, something like that, the regular services.
There were quite a few of the faculty that attended the preb here in church that you'd know.
Bolton was one of them, Dean Bolton.
and D.W. Williams, who was quite prominent.
And, let's see, I guess he'd become, he was Chancellor of Agriculture, I remember, I don't, I remember just how.
Cashians.
And the Cashians, of course, yeah, certainly.
And, um,
Then there were some department heads.
Guy Adrian, are you familiar with him?
He was head of horticulture.
Ross Sherwood, he was in the experiment station in the animal science area.
President Morgan also attended there when he was, well, that's later on.
Describe Brother Anderson as the minister.
describe him in personality and so forth and style?
He was a Scotchman and quite definite in his concepts and statements and he was I'd say conscientious and committed to his role as a minister.
His
of appeal was perhaps not as great as one might expect from a student standpoint of the type of individual that would appeal most to students at that age.
Colonel Anderson was also a member of that company, wasn't he?
He sure was.
Thank you.
These names just don't come up.
If you can jog my memory, it helps.
Yes, he and his wife, Helen Anderson, who was quite a delightful lady, were members.
And I always remember and have high regard for Colonel, we called him Colonel Andy at the time.
He was the commandant just for a couple of years, as I recall.
But one of the years that I was an undergraduate here,

And I have forgotten the incident, but these kind of things used to occur, not constantly, but occasionally if some disagreement or the Corps got upset about something, they didn't march on the house like they did with Gilchrist later.
But anyway, Colonel Landy was commandant, and he was on the other side of the argument with the Corps.
And he was, I thought, treated unreasonably.
He'd come out there during this particular period, I recall, come out and stand in the center of the campus there as the representation of authority, and he was either booed or mistreated.
He just happened to be on the other side.
He was insisting on probably some adherence to some regulation or rule, and the cadets, of course, weren't always too enthused about that.
But I think he was generally well-liked, but he did get crossways with his students sometimes.
You all had a Presbyterian Sunday night activity.
Right.
Was there also a worship service on Sunday night?
No, I don't recall there being.
Oh, one thing I wanted to include about the religious part that I'd overlooked that
did illustrate, demonstrate the interest of the institution in religious activities.
And that was the, I've forgotten the name they had for it, but it was a week of Christian ministry.
Religious emphasis week.
RE week, yeah.
And each major denomination would have one of their renowned pastors from somewhere in the United States come.
And then there'd be one major speaker who would speak to the cadet corps every morning at 10 o'clock, I'll say, in Guyon Hall.
And it'd be Phil.
It really would be.
And these were outstanding people.
And if you ask me who one of them was, I can remember one.
Lewis Evans was here one time.
But I
I can't remember the names of the others, but it was quite an important event, and I don't know whether they'd be allowed to do that sort of thing nowadays.
I'm afraid so, but it really was a great occasion, and the thing that impressed me about it, looking back at that time, was the students responded.
There was good attendance, and then at the individual churches...
there would be attendance.

As I recall, using Presbyterian for example since that's the one I'm familiar with, we'd have a speaker from somewhere large congregation throughout the country and he would speak each night at the local congregation and we'd have both students and members or the public invited as far as that goes.
Did y'all go to a Wednesday, was there a Wednesday night of service?
I cannot remember that there was.
I don't, I remember the evening services, but I think they're on, just on Sunday evenings.
Now there might be on occasion special call meetings, you know, Wednesday night.
Do you remember going to football games that first year up here?
Yes, I can't remember a lot of detail about them, except we stood up all the time, which I soon learned that part of it.
And I believe I went to most of them, and surprisingly I had somewhat mixed emotions that first year when we played Rice.
I couldn't quite get over the fact that I almost favored Rice at the time, having been there for some years.
And if I recall, that was when Rice had some pretty good teams along in there.
I think they went to Cotton Bowl one year along in there, 37 or 38.
What about court trips?
Did you make court trips?
Yes.
As I recall, there would be just one or two in the fall, though.
And I remember one...

Well, we always had a court trip when we played in Austin, and I remember going there, and I remember marching down Congress, whatever avenue we marched, and that's about all of it I can remember at this time.
I think we had one in Houston and probably one in Dallas during that period of time.
Do you remember going to Silver Taps?
What impression did that make?
I thought it was a great tradition.
It surely did.
And very moving and impressive.
It had an impact on the core, on the students, I believe.
What about Bonfire in that era?
Well, I can't separate it from 60 years of Bonfire very well.
Well, I haven't been here all that time, but I can recall Bonfire, but I'm almost certain it was after I graduated.
A number of people have told me that before World War II, it was primarily a collection of rubbish, trash.
Oh, that part.
I think about the occasion itself.
it was nothing like these monumental things that are built now and, uh, would have, would just be a big, big bonfire.
That's about all you could say of it.
Not a, I certainly don't.
Uh, I'm not sure that I did.
Uh,
But it was, you know, you didn't have to requisition half the cadet corps to spend three weeks or whatever length of time.

It now has been a recent experience, and I don't know just where that all came in, but it was not an activity that totally, or say totally, or significantly disrupted student life for a while where there was, I don't know how many,
thousand, I guess, of man and woman hours put in on it now, but I don't recall anything of that nature back then.
I guess I do, I just recall the event and the football players getting up and making a few comments.
Now, I'm assuming since you were, those undergraduate years were the fall of 36, you graduated in the spring of 38.
That's correct, in June.
I'm assuming that since World War II hadn't started yet, that you all didn't think that much about what was happening on the other side of the world.
You weren't worried yet about World War II?
During that 36 to 38?
No, I would say that wasn't a big factor, although I guess by the time I graduated in the spring of 38...

There was, I'd say, some realization of it, and the students were much more interested in being sure they got a commission financially and otherwise, but there was a good deal of competition for it, and all the students who performed reasonably well were able to get commissions at that time, and I believe quite a few went on into the service after graduation in 1938.
Right now...
Did you have any, was there any awkwardness in your getting an Aggie senior rank?
No, I don't recall any.
I want to be sure and include this comment.
I may have given a totally negative impression of coming in here as a transfer.
I was treated very considerably by the Corps members as an individual, them as individuals, me as an individual.
It was just a situation you just didn't fit in anywhere precisely, and...
That was just part of it, but individually, whether they were seniors or freshmen or what, they treated me... Did you acquire a nickname?
I was called Johnny, if that's a...
But nothing else?
No, not these real exotic nicknames.
Not Cotton Topper?
Topper.
Arkansas.
There's one thing I want to mention.
I don't know whether this...
occurred right after I graduated.
I just went to two years in the spring of 38.
I was taking mainly senior courses then.
Are you familiar with the Cotton Tour?
Well, in the 30s, it was, I think, originated in the early 30s, perhaps.

By 38, this is probably the 8th or 10th tour, I don't recall which, but it had been started primarily by Professor Mogford, who was the cotton expert and thought it would be a great thing to publicize the university and to reward students and get information out on the
the major crop of the state at that time and of course the primary force in agriculture almost then.
So he originated this cotton tour I'm going to say about 1930 probably.
And the concept was that there would be examinations given over different phases of cotton production and development and so forth.
And these were

somewhat difficult exams and were given during the spring and were open for competition by any students and I entered the competition without any thought of winning since well one I hadn't been there all four years so I didn't think I'd absorbed as much as some of the others would have but anyway we went through the spring taking these exams I think once a week say they'd be cotton pathology and
entomology and production and breeding and spinning and all those things.
Believe it or not, I was one of the winners.
There were three, just three winners.
In retrospect, particularly, that was probably the greatest award you could have received from A&M as far as actual benefit.
We managed a 10-week paid tour
during the summer immediately after taking the exams and those who had qualified.
So that was a real privilege and something I'll always remember.
This is right after you graduated?
Right immediately afterward.
anticipating marriage at the time.
I don't know whether you knew Margaret or not.
She probably passed away just before you came back here.
Summer of 97, I guess.
Anyway, we had been going.
